00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:56.300
and how it makes us feel?

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:58.630
And for me, it's a
really personal journey,

00:02:58.630 --> 00:02:59.860
like it is for everyone.

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:01.710
And food is such
a personal thing.

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:03.969
But basically over
the last 20 years

00:03:03.969 --> 00:03:05.760
I've been suffering
from some health things

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:08.650
that no one could
really explain.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:10.130
We joke that I kind
of look normal,

00:03:10.130 --> 00:03:11.190
but I didn't feel normal.

00:03:11.190 --> 00:03:11.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:15.180
So you know, allergies,
and asthma, and eczema,

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:18.400
and then I started getting
chronic heartburn as I aged.

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:20.969
And then got signs of
rheumatoid arthritis

00:03:20.969 --> 00:03:22.010
that we couldn't explain.

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:25.032
So all of these problems, and
back problems my whole life.

00:03:25.032 --> 00:03:27.240
And it was so interesting
because I tried everything.

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:29.990
I tried all kinds
of regular medicine.

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:32.120
I tried East meets
West-- acupuncture,

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:34.340
acupressure, physical therapy.

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:36.740
And about seven years ago I
walked into an allergist's

00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:39.450
office, and I started
listing my ailments,

00:03:39.450 --> 00:03:41.880
and I was crying because
about once a year I

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:43.720
would just be so upset
about this, wondering

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:45.360
why can't I get better?

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:47.680
And he stopped me, and
he said, Amanda, there's

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:49.340
some really good news here.

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:51.740
Everything that you're
talking about is inflammation.

00:03:51.740 --> 00:03:54.320
It's just a different form
of inflammation in your body.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:57.640
And all that meant was
that your body is reacting

00:03:57.640 --> 00:03:59.080
to some outside irritant.

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:00.377
So he said, guess what?

00:04:00.377 --> 00:04:00.960
You're a cook.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:01.882
You can fix this.

00:04:01.882 --> 00:04:03.590
I know that there's
something that you're

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:05.880
eating that is making
you feel terrible.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:08.500
And it's showing itself in all
of these ridiculous things that

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:09.900
are going on with you.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:11.246
So he sent me away.

00:04:11.246 --> 00:04:13.120
And he also said, and
once you figure it out,

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:14.100
you've got to do
something about it.

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:16.016
You've got to like shout
it from the rooftops,

00:04:16.016 --> 00:04:17.089
if you can fix this.

00:04:17.089 --> 00:04:18.579
So he told me, quit gluten.

00:04:18.579 --> 00:04:20.870
I don't want you having a
bite of gluten for two weeks,

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:22.100
and tell me what happens.

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:24.740
And fortunately
or unfortunately,

00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:26.860
the changes were so
profound within two days,

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:28.300
I couldn't even believe it.

00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:31.010
And so I was almost
angry at myself

00:04:31.010 --> 00:04:33.150
that that's the last
thing that I'd turned to.

00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:36.350
That I used food as my last
solution, instead of the first.

00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:39.170
And so what happened is
it became super empowering

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:41.820
to know that what I was eating
could make me feel great,

00:04:41.820 --> 00:04:44.570
or it could make me feel
terrible really quickly.

00:04:44.570 --> 00:04:48.410
And that every choice I make
when I sit down at the table

00:04:48.410 --> 00:04:50.130
affects my well-being.

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:53.080
So this book is a
culmination of that journey.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:55.130
And hopefully it
pertains to a lot of us

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:57.180
because it's not just
about what I can't have,

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:00.310
or what I can have, it's
more about explaining

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:02.990
what's gone on with food,
and why so many of us

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:04.710
are reacting to
different types of food

00:05:04.710 --> 00:05:07.060
now that we didn't used
to have problems with.

00:05:07.060 --> 00:05:09.370
And the whole idea
that, let's explain it

00:05:09.370 --> 00:05:12.550
with this great doctor who has
spoken to Google before Dr.

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:13.810
Bradley Jacobs.

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:16.225
He talks about the ingredients,
and why a lot of us

00:05:16.225 --> 00:05:16.850
are struggling.

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:18.860
And then I say, let's just
throw those out the window,

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:21.590
and let's cook with ingredients
that make us feel really great.

00:05:21.590 --> 00:05:24.190
So Gusteau said anyone can cook.

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:25.750
I think if I had
a motto mine would

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:27.350
be, I want people
to say about me,

00:05:27.350 --> 00:05:29.020
her food tastes
so good you don't

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:31.150
care that it's good for you.

00:05:31.150 --> 00:05:32.851
It's just delicious,
