00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:43.100
Is there an oil I
prefer to cook with?

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:45.280
So I talk about different
oils in the book.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:48.400
I love olive oil for a
lot of the things I do.

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:50.800
I'm using canola oil in this,
which has some great health

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:52.410
benefits as well.

00:09:52.410 --> 00:09:54.380
It's a really
neutral tasting oil.

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:57.210
So if I don't want the oil to
be the strong flavor in it,

00:09:57.210 --> 00:09:59.060
I'll usually cook with canola.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:01.660
And the one thing that
I look for in oils, I do

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:05.150
look for organic and non-GMO
because so many of those things

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:07.530
can be sprayed so
heavily with pesticides.

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:08.491
Canola is one of those.

00:10:08.491 --> 00:10:10.240
So there are some great
ones on the market

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:12.156
now that you can find
at your local store that

00:10:12.156 --> 00:10:15.730
say non-GMO and organic for a
fairly inexpensive price, which

00:10:15.730 --> 00:10:16.630
is great.

00:10:16.630 --> 00:10:18.800
So can you see how that
all just looks dark.

00:10:18.800 --> 00:10:21.440
And look at all that stuff
on the bottom of the pan, all

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:22.940
that brown stuff.

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:25.300
It's what I like to
call yummy goodness.

00:10:25.300 --> 00:10:27.259
JENNA: Yum yums, I think
is the technical term.

00:10:27.259 --> 00:10:28.050
AMANDA HAAS: It is.

00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:29.130
I'm pretty sure it is.

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:30.671
JENNA: The yum
yums at the bottom

00:10:30.671 --> 00:10:32.170
AMANDA HAAS: And
so basically that's

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:33.570
all of that
caramelized goodness.

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:35.070
And you don't want
to get rid of it.

00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:37.920
You want to be able to bring it
into the flavors of what you're

00:10:37.920 --> 00:10:39.420
making.

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:42.120
The fancy term of what I
just did, we're deglazing.

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:45.230
And so see how I can
lift off all of that.

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:46.840
I put some cold
liquid in the pan,

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:50.260
and it's going to react with
the food on the bottom of it,

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:52.090
and just lift it right up.

00:10:52.090 --> 00:10:54.500
So I just put in a little
of my liquid to start.

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:57.690
And all of that is going to
become part of this foundation

00:10:57.690 --> 00:11:02.780
for this curry,
which is delicious.

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:04.950
So whether you're doing a
vegetarian dish like this,

00:11:04.950 --> 00:11:07.460
or you're doing something that's
meat-based, like a protein,

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:09.370
you know steak, beef
caramelizes really

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:13.430
well like that, you want all of
that back up into your sauce.

00:11:13.430 --> 00:11:15.070
We would never want
to throw it away

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:17.346
unless you happen
to really burn it.

00:11:17.346 --> 00:11:19.249
You would have to start fresh.

00:11:19.249 --> 00:11:21.790
But now that it's in I'm going
to crank this up a little bit,

00:11:21.790 --> 00:11:24.030
and add the rest of my liquids.

00:11:24.030 --> 00:11:24.620
OK, great.

00:11:24.620 --> 00:11:26.078
So I'm going to
bring it up to high

00:11:26.078 --> 00:11:28.065
just to bring it to a simmer.

00:11:31.310 --> 00:11:33.350
Water is a very
underutilized ingredient

00:11:33.350 --> 00:11:34.310
I think when you cook.

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:36.580
And it's kind of like were
just talking about oils.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.270
When you want something neutral,
but you need the liquid,

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:40.879
don't forget about it right.

00:11:40.879 --> 00:11:42.920
You could certainly do
chicken stock or vegetable

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:44.199
stock, if you wanted.

00:11:44.199 --> 00:11:46.240
But you're adding another
flavor component there.

00:11:46.240 --> 00:11:48.450
So I'll use water
when I don't have

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:50.680
stock for things like risotto.

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:54.020
You can totally use it to
interchange with things.

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:55.830
And I just don't
want stock competing

00:11:55.830 --> 00:11:59.339
with these other flavors that
I've got going on in the pot.

00:11:59.339 --> 00:12:00.130
JENNA: Interesting.

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:00.879
AMANDA HAAS: Yeah.

00:12:00.879 --> 00:12:04.070
So now what we're going to do is
just add a couple more liquids.

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:06.120
And this is so easy
in that you're just

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:07.740
putting a bunch of
things in at once,

00:12:07.740 --> 00:12:08.920
and then we're going
to let it simmer.

00:12:08.920 --> 00:12:10.700
We're going to add
the other components.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:11.907
Coconut milk.

00:12:11.907 --> 00:12:13.490
You guys can read
in the book as well,

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:15.730
coconut oil got a really
bad rap for a long time

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:16.920
because we were refining it.

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:19.910
But it is we're finding
basically that great rule

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:21.550
of thumb that if it
comes from nature,

00:12:21.550 --> 00:12:22.700
it's probably good for you.

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:24.040
JENNA: Yeah, if
you leave it alone.

00:12:24.040 --> 00:12:25.790
AMANDA HAAS: Right,
if you leave it alone.

00:12:25.790 --> 00:12:28.170
And so coconut oil is
having a total comeback.

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:29.872
JENNA: Oh yeah,
so hot right now.

00:12:29.872 --> 00:12:31.330
AMANDA HAAS: It's
so hot right now.

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:32.450
It really is.

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:34.350
Coconut milk, I
love cooking with.

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:37.100
And again, it's giving you
that awesome depth of flavor,

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:38.980
and some fat to add
flavor when you're

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:41.520
cooking vegetarian things.

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:44.390
Fat is flavor, as we like to
say in the culinary world.

00:12:44.390 --> 00:12:47.850
And so I think a lot of people
when they love to crave steak,

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:50.029
and crave chicken
with skin, and things

00:12:50.029 --> 00:12:52.320
like that, it's the fat that
we love in our diet, which

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:53.880
can be really good for us.

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:57.640
But I love to look for
things that can replace them.

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:00.080
I'm going to add some lime
juice too for the acid,

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.304
so it balances the
richness of the coconut.

00:13:03.304 --> 00:13:05.470
And then, Jenna, I wasn't
talking to you about this.

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:06.345
Who was I talking to?

00:13:06.345 --> 00:13:06.950
Oh, with Chef.

00:13:06.950 --> 00:13:08.491
I was talking to
Chef Didi about this

00:13:08.491 --> 00:13:12.255
at the beginning, how agave
syrup is already a hot thing.

00:13:12.255 --> 00:13:14.380
We're already starting to
see in the food community

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:16.660
that we're probably not
that crazy about it anymore.

00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:19.650
And that the best natural
sweeteners are honey and maple

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:21.744
syrup, as you find
them in nature.

00:13:21.744 --> 00:13:23.660
And so it's interesting
because they think now

00:13:23.660 --> 00:13:25.610
agave syrup can spike
your blood sugar

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:27.165
in ways that were
not crazy about.

00:13:27.165 --> 00:13:28.440
JENNA: That's so interesting.

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:29.040
AMANDA HAAS: Right?

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:30.581
Because it's got
more fructose in it.

00:13:30.581 --> 00:13:32.950
JENNA: Yeah, but that
was kind of counter

00:13:32.950 --> 00:13:34.640
indicated a couple years ago.

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:36.104
AMANDA HAAS: Exactly.

00:13:36.104 --> 00:13:37.770
JENNA: You always
have to pay attention.

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:39.195
The food world
evolves so quickly.

00:13:39.195 --> 00:13:40.570
AMANDA HAAS: It
does, and I think

00:13:40.570 --> 00:13:42.330
you can't chase every trend.

00:13:42.330 --> 00:13:44.730
But I think, again, it comes
back to some common sense.

00:13:44.730 --> 00:13:47.350
And what I loved about having
a doctor partner with me

00:13:47.350 --> 00:13:51.030
on the book is that he could
kind of prove my hypotheses.

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:52.510
And he was saying,
you know stick

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:55.051
to things that are natural, and
just don't use a ton of them.

00:13:55.051 --> 00:13:56.870
So agave I was using.

00:13:56.870 --> 00:13:59.610
But I've switched
to honey at home,

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:01.504
and I put maple
syrup when I need to.

00:14:01.504 --> 00:14:02.795
I put maple syrup in my coffee.

00:14:02.795 --> 00:14:04.490
I don't know why I
think that's tasty.

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:05.074
But I love it.

00:14:05.074 --> 00:14:06.073
JENNA: That's delicious.

00:14:06.073 --> 00:14:07.460
AMANDA HAAS: Yeah,
so we're going

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:10.740
to do a little agave for sweet.

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:12.770
And just bring this up
to a simmer before I add

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:14.240
the lentils.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:16.560
And then we're going to
let those cook for about 10

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:17.840
or 15 minutes on their own.

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:20.290
And then just put in some
vegetables to finish it off.

00:14:20.290 --> 00:14:21.730
And that's the dish.

00:14:21.730 --> 00:14:24.067
So it's pretty straightforward.

00:14:24.067 --> 00:14:26.400
The one thing to keep in mind
as you're making something

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:28.610
like this is that you can
totally make it your own.

00:14:28.610 --> 00:14:31.130
So a lot of times we'll
do chicken in this.

00:14:31.130 --> 00:14:33.990
If I have a chicken or I roast
a chicken, I'll add part of that

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:35.600
into this dish.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:37.970
You could do tofu,
if you are vegetarian

00:14:37.970 --> 00:14:40.160
and you want another
source of protein.

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:42.680
You can switch up your veggies
to whatever's seasonal.

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:43.620
JENNA: Sure.

00:14:43.620 --> 00:14:45.120
AMANDA HAAS: If you
want more color,

00:14:45.120 --> 00:14:47.099
I'll put broccoli in it
instead of cauliflower.

00:14:47.099 --> 00:14:48.390
JENNA: Bell pepper even, maybe.

00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:49.830
AMANDA HAAS: Bell pepper
would be delicious.

00:14:49.830 --> 00:14:51.288
And I would probably
cook those off

00:14:51.288 --> 00:14:54.160
with the onion at the beginning
just to kind of caramelize

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:56.810
and sweeten those
up a little bit.

00:14:56.810 --> 00:14:57.932
So far so good?

00:14:57.932 --> 00:14:59.640
JENNA: Curry can be
a good kitchen clean.

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:02.140
Like, oh what do I have
in the veggie basket?

00:15:02.140 --> 00:15:03.857
AMANDA HAAS: I totally
agree with you.

00:15:03.857 --> 00:15:05.190
And that's normally how I do it.

00:15:05.190 --> 00:15:06.580
I was laughing when I saw
this recipe because I'm

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:08.121
like, when's the
last time I actually

00:15:08.121 --> 00:15:10.535
cooked the recipe like this?

00:15:10.535 --> 00:15:12.800
I was like it's
normally I always

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:14.700
have something green
in my refrigerator.

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:17.284
Or the other thing I love
to do is roast vegetables

00:15:17.284 --> 00:15:19.200
off at a really high
heat because, again, they

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:20.560
get caramelized and sweet.

00:15:20.560 --> 00:15:23.260
So if you think people
don't like cauliflower,

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:27.850
I don't know if you like
cauliflower over here,

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:29.760
roasted it's a lot sweeter.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:31.470
So you can always
roast off vegetables,

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:33.511
and then put them in here
at the last minute too.

00:15:33.511 --> 00:15:35.330
And it gives a different
element of flavor.

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:37.370
So you can see that
everything's simmering now,

00:15:37.370 --> 00:15:40.020
which is right what I want.

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:41.390
Got my water.

00:15:41.390 --> 00:15:43.927
Do we have a lid
for this big pot?

00:15:43.927 --> 00:15:44.510
We'll get one.

00:15:44.510 --> 00:15:45.840
Thank you, Chef.

00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:49.280
And all I'm going to do is
turn it down with the lid on.

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:51.100
And let it simmer,
which means I just

00:15:51.100 --> 00:15:53.580
want a little bit of a bubble
going when the lid's on.

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:55.610
If steam is coming
out of it like crazy,

00:15:55.610 --> 00:15:57.380
you'll know that
we are cooking it

00:15:57.380 --> 00:15:59.800
at too high of a temperature.

00:15:59.800 --> 00:16:01.530
So can someone be my
volunteer to watch

00:16:01.530 --> 00:16:03.670
the clock for about
10 minutes, 10 or 15,

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:07.150
and let me when time's up?

00:16:07.150 --> 00:16:07.790
Thank you.

00:16:07.790 --> 00:16:09.756
Thank you, lovely
assistant over there.

00:16:09.756 --> 00:16:11.340
JENNA: Thank you.

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:13.940
AMANDA HAAS: So let's
put a lid on it.

00:16:13.940 --> 00:16:16.720
And then we'll move
on to another recipe

00:16:16.720 --> 00:16:18.800
while we're waiting
for this one to finish.

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:20.130
I think three will be good.

00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:21.330
OK, great.

00:16:21.330 --> 00:16:23.420
So this literally when
it's done cooking there,

00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:24.840
we're just going to
add our vegetables in.

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:25.970
And then I'm going
to teach you how

00:16:25.970 --> 00:16:28.490
to season it, and taste for
flavorings at the end of it.

00:16:28.490 --> 00:16:31.660
But great recipe to take home,
and make your own, and really

00:16:31.660 --> 00:16:33.480
just practice kind of
the foundation of it,

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:34.470
and going from there.

00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:36.680
JENNA: And what would you
generally serve that with?

00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:39.054
AMANDA HAAS: So I like to
serve it kind of as the entree.

00:16:39.054 --> 00:16:42.380
And today you will try
it with some brown rice.

00:16:42.380 --> 00:16:44.900
So it's really nice if you
want to do it like that.

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:47.320
This would be a really typical
weeknight meal in my house

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:48.653
because you could make it ahead.

00:16:48.653 --> 00:16:51.630
And actually the flavors
develop even more, which I love.

00:16:51.630 --> 00:16:54.030
So with some rice,
or even quinoa

00:16:54.030 --> 00:16:56.670
if you wanted on the
side would be great.

00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:58.660
It'd be really great.

00:16:58.660 --> 00:17:01.160
We're just going to do
a little change here.

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:02.860
And then let's talk
about our quinoa

00:17:02.860 --> 00:17:06.069
while we get ready to
do the whole salad.

00:17:06.069 --> 00:17:08.560
Who here likes quinoa?

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:09.839
Yeah.

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:10.980
It's been a total change.

00:17:10.980 --> 00:17:12.020
No, shaking your head.

00:17:12.020 --> 00:17:14.530
You're in the same camp
I was for a long time.

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:16.319
So when the lovely
doctor told me

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:18.430
I couldn't have gluten
anymore, my first thought

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:20.874
was I was going to
get fired from my job

00:17:20.874 --> 00:17:24.200
because we create
products all day long

00:17:24.200 --> 00:17:25.250
that are full of gluten.

00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:29.180
You know like amazing baked
goods, and cookies, and bread.

00:17:29.180 --> 00:17:30.386
So that was my first fear.

00:17:30.386 --> 00:17:31.760
And then my second
was that I was

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:34.500
going to have to learn how to
like quinoa because it really

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:35.870
never did it for me.

00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:37.060
I love couscous.

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:39.870
I love all those great
grain salads you could get.

00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:41.700
But a couple of tricks,
which I learned,

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:42.756
which are so much better.

00:17:42.756 --> 00:17:44.130
And Jenna, do you
mind handing me

00:17:44.130 --> 00:17:46.530
that chinois, that big sieve
that's down on the end?

00:17:46.530 --> 00:17:48.030
Thank you so much.

00:17:48.030 --> 00:17:52.400
One is that quinoa naturally
has a natural pesticide

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:53.760
on it called saponins.

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:56.184
And when you rinse the
quinoa, you rinse that off.

00:17:56.184 --> 00:17:58.100
So if any of you ever
had it, and you're like,

00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:00.266
there's this taste about
it that you just don't like

00:18:00.266 --> 00:18:01.740
or I can't identify,
it's probably

00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:03.459
the saponins on the quinoa.

00:18:03.459 --> 00:18:04.250
JENNA: Fascinating.

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:05.190
AMANDA HAAS: Weird, right?

00:18:05.190 --> 00:18:05.930
JENNA: Yeah, I never heard that.

00:18:05.930 --> 00:18:08.346
AMANDA HAAS: Right, so it's
like to rinse or not to rinse?

00:18:08.346 --> 00:18:09.740
Now, to rinse is what I say.

00:18:09.740 --> 00:18:11.710
So you rinse those off.

00:18:11.710 --> 00:18:15.130
And then it's a really
easy formula for cooking.

00:18:15.130 --> 00:18:16.590
And it's just like rice.

00:18:16.590 --> 00:18:18.920
So I love formulas
when I'm cooking,

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:20.837
just so that you do it
once, and you remember.

00:18:20.837 --> 00:18:22.878
JENNA: I think you're
speaking to the right crowd

00:18:22.878 --> 00:18:23.696
in that regard.

00:18:23.696 --> 00:18:25.890
AMANDA HAAS: Am I?

00:18:25.890 --> 00:18:26.440
I love it.

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:29.023
I love having a foundation, and
then you can make it your own.

00:18:29.023 --> 00:18:31.360
But with quinoa, like rice,
all you're going to do

00:18:31.360 --> 00:18:33.590
is two parts water
to one part quinoa.

00:18:33.590 --> 00:18:34.720
It's that simple.

00:18:34.720 --> 00:18:37.010
And a little bit of
salt. Again, if you

00:18:37.010 --> 00:18:42.610
wanted to put it in a stock you
could if you want more flavor

00:18:42.610 --> 00:18:43.110
in that.

00:18:43.110 --> 00:18:47.410
I usually just do it with water,
and then a little bit of salt,

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:48.810
and you're good to go.

00:18:48.810 --> 00:18:51.880
So I'm just going to put
this right in the pot.

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:54.122
And then I'm going
to eyeball my water.

00:18:54.122 --> 00:18:55.580
You know what I
love about cooking,

00:18:55.580 --> 00:18:58.560
and this is why I'm not a great
baker, because it doesn't have

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:00.600
to be that exact all the time.

00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:03.630
It's OK to eyeball things,
or change out ingredients

00:19:03.630 --> 00:19:06.320
when you have something else.

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:08.830
So you start with
that foundation,

00:19:08.830 --> 00:19:11.110
and then you get to
make it your own.

00:19:11.110 --> 00:19:13.420
Put this over here.

00:19:13.420 --> 00:19:15.670
Jenna, I'm going to have you
watch some of this stuff.

00:19:15.670 --> 00:19:17.820
No actually, I'm going to put
you to work on the vinaigrette

00:19:17.820 --> 00:19:18.140
as well.

00:19:18.140 --> 00:19:18.660
I forgot--

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:18.740
JENNA: I don't know.

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:20.640
AMANDA HAAS: --I have
another job for you.

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:23.730
So this is literally how
we're going to do this, folks.

00:19:23.730 --> 00:19:26.234
Two parts water.

00:19:26.234 --> 00:19:27.150
JENNA: Very technical.

00:19:27.150 --> 00:19:29.790
AMANDA HAAS: Very,
very technical, right?

00:19:29.790 --> 00:19:33.185
Pinch of salt. I always keep
salt and pepper at the cooktop.

00:19:33.185 --> 00:19:35.310
You know they're going to
be your best friends when

00:19:35.310 --> 00:19:36.220
you cook.

00:19:36.220 --> 00:19:39.610
And another thing to remember
is that you taste all the time

00:19:39.610 --> 00:19:40.110
as a cook.

00:19:40.110 --> 00:19:43.400
You know if you wait until the
end sometimes it's too late.

00:19:43.400 --> 00:19:45.360
So you want to be
tasting as you go.

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:46.920
And you'll watch me
taste the lentils

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:48.650
before I add the
veggies back in just

00:19:48.650 --> 00:19:50.470
to kind of see where
we are on the flavors.

00:19:50.470 --> 00:19:52.500
I'm pretty sure it's
going to need salt.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:55.470
And I'll do the same
thing as I cook and make

00:19:55.470 --> 00:19:56.610
these other things for you.

00:19:56.610 --> 00:19:58.460
So always make
sure you're tasting

00:19:58.460 --> 00:20:00.350
and adjusting as you go.

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:02.470
Now let's see if I can
use this fancy cooktop.

00:20:02.470 --> 00:20:03.362
I can.

00:20:03.362 --> 00:20:05.070
JENNA: So how long
for quinoa, generally?

00:20:05.070 --> 00:20:07.153
AMANDA HAAS: So quinoa is
really easy in that it's

00:20:07.153 --> 00:20:10.120
about 15 to 20 minutes.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:12.140
Can you guys see
actually on my spoon

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:14.940
how are these tiny, cute,
little grains right?

00:20:14.940 --> 00:20:16.800
They're actually seeds.

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:17.900
It's going to split.

00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:19.710
And it's going to give
this cute little white seam

00:20:19.710 --> 00:20:20.584
on the outside of it.

00:20:20.584 --> 00:20:22.714
So all we're looking
for it to do is split.

00:20:22.714 --> 00:20:25.130
And you can overcook it just
like you'd overcook anything.

00:20:25.130 --> 00:20:26.890
It's certainly not
the end of the world.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:30.190
But I'm probably going to
check it at about 12 minutes.

00:20:30.190 --> 00:20:32.740
And then let it
go as long as 20.

00:20:32.740 --> 00:20:37.067
So we'll see how
hot this cooktop is,

00:20:37.067 --> 00:20:37.900
and give it a whirl.

00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:40.820
I'm going to let that come to a
boil before I put a lid on it.

00:20:40.820 --> 00:20:42.410
JENNA: All right,
what's the plan?

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:44.243
AMANDA HAAS: So the
next plan, what we'll do

00:20:44.243 --> 00:20:46.130
is we'll make the
vinaigrette for the quinoa

00:20:46.130 --> 00:20:48.399
while we're waiting for
these other things to cook.

00:20:48.399 --> 00:20:50.315
How many of you have
made vinaigrettes before?

00:20:52.930 --> 00:20:54.359
Yeah, OK, fantastic.

00:20:54.359 --> 00:20:55.900
One of the things
that I love, Jenna,

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:58.389
is that if you go and you buy
salad dressing or vinaigrette

00:20:58.389 --> 00:21:00.180
at the store, it's one
of those things that

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:02.430
can be loaded with
sodium and salt.

00:21:02.430 --> 00:21:04.980
And you don't need the
extra fillers in them.

00:21:04.980 --> 00:21:07.320
They're so easy to make at home.

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:09.170
When people ask me
what's one of the best

00:21:09.170 --> 00:21:11.340
things you could do
for yourself at home,

00:21:11.340 --> 00:21:12.710
I say make vinaigrettes.

00:21:12.710 --> 00:21:14.340
And you can do a big batch.

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:16.520
I love to just make
a huge thing of it.

00:21:16.520 --> 00:21:18.592
And again, it's about
proportions and ratios.

00:21:18.592 --> 00:21:19.800
So we're going to learn that.

00:21:19.800 --> 00:21:22.760
And then you just
keep them around.

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:25.910
Oh, I love how everything
is made for us here.

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:26.466
It's amazing.

00:21:26.466 --> 00:21:28.215
Do you want to bring
this up here for you?

00:21:28.215 --> 00:21:28.715
JENNA: Sure.

00:21:28.715 --> 00:21:30.890
AMANDA HAAS: And then I'm
going to grab the garlic.

00:21:30.890 --> 00:21:35.217
And then we're going to just do
one really basic vinaigrette.

00:21:35.217 --> 00:21:36.800
People always ask
me, especially where

00:21:36.800 --> 00:21:39.879
I work at Williams-Sonoma, we
sell the most amazing tools

00:21:39.879 --> 00:21:41.420
ever, they're like
what do you really

00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:42.710
have to have in your kitchen?

00:21:42.710 --> 00:21:45.720
Like a knife, a great knife A
great knife and a great cutting

00:21:45.720 --> 00:21:46.220
board.

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:47.200
I love both things.

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:49.500
So I'm going to show you a
little trick today with one

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:50.360
of my favorite knives.

00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:52.609
And first, I'm going to just
push down on that garlic.

00:21:52.609 --> 00:21:53.620
See how I do that?

00:21:53.620 --> 00:21:57.190
Because I want to mince it, and
I want to get it really fine.

00:21:57.190 --> 00:21:59.250
But this salt is going
to act as an abrasive.

00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:00.890
So when you go to
chop it it's just

00:22:00.890 --> 00:22:02.670
going to kind of like
bring it together.

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:04.382
It's really, really easy.

00:22:04.382 --> 00:22:06.090
And then I'm going to
have you finish off

00:22:06.090 --> 00:22:07.050
the vinaigrette for us.

00:22:07.050 --> 00:22:08.070
JENNA: For sure,
that's a fun trick.

00:22:08.070 --> 00:22:09.097
I didn't know that one.

00:22:09.097 --> 00:22:11.180
AMANDA HAAS: It's kind of
like a little chef hack.

00:22:11.180 --> 00:22:12.810
You look really
serious and fancy,

00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:15.370
and it's not that hard to do.

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:19.730
Can I get a second timer for my
quinoa please for 12 minutes?

00:22:19.730 --> 00:22:20.784
Thank you.

00:22:20.784 --> 00:22:23.200
All right so I just sprinkled
a little bit of kosher salt.

00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:25.570
Kosher salt's got a
larger grain to it.

00:22:25.570 --> 00:22:27.050
And I put that on the garlic.

00:22:27.050 --> 00:22:28.508
And now watch what
I'm going to do.

00:22:28.508 --> 00:22:30.140
I'm just going to
start chopping.

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:31.690
You can hold it.

00:22:31.690 --> 00:22:33.320
You guys see how I'm
holding the knife?

00:22:33.320 --> 00:22:37.020
Just got my thumb and my index
finger around it like this.

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:38.522
It creates stability.

00:22:38.522 --> 00:22:40.480
And what you'll see is
that all I'm going to do

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:42.000
is rock my wrist.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.400
I'm not going to be taking
the knife up like this.

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:47.190
You can usually just keep the
tip of your knife on the board.

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:49.520
And you let your
wrist do the work.

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:51.950
So I'm just going to
start to chop this.

00:22:51.950 --> 00:22:54.040
But it would be a lot
more slippery if I

00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:57.080
didn't have the salt on it.

00:22:57.080 --> 00:23:00.740
And then what you can do is
kind of press all this together.

00:23:00.740 --> 00:23:03.050
And this is going to help
me form like really finally

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:04.469
chopped pieces of garlic.

00:23:04.469 --> 00:23:05.260
JENNA: Fascinating.

00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:06.801
AMANDA HAAS: So if
you do a ton of it

00:23:06.801 --> 00:23:09.420
at once it's actually easier
if you have a bunch of cloves

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:12.190
because you've got more surface
area kind of to work with.

00:23:12.190 --> 00:23:14.460
But I just kind of press it.

00:23:14.460 --> 00:23:15.530
It's kind of fun, right?

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:17.490
You look really
grown up and serious.

00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:20.730
Morgan over there has
got this mastered.

00:23:20.730 --> 00:23:21.810
So great.

00:23:21.810 --> 00:23:25.390
Just keep bringing it back
together and chopping away.

00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:29.955
I just don't want really
huge chunks of it.

00:23:29.955 --> 00:23:32.080
So when you're eating the
salad, you're like, whoa,

00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:35.860
I just got so much garlic.

00:23:35.860 --> 00:23:39.020
Again, it's so great for
just digestion garlic is.

00:23:39.020 --> 00:23:41.790
And so I try to use
it whenever I can.

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:45.820
And in vinaigrettes it adds
a great layer of flavor.

00:23:45.820 --> 00:23:48.500
OK, so I'm putting
this in as my base

00:23:48.500 --> 00:23:50.720
because this is one
of my favorites.

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:53.327
Who's ready to talk formula?

00:23:53.327 --> 00:23:54.160
JENNA: What you got?

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:56.294
AMANDA HAAS: OK, really easy.

00:23:56.294 --> 00:23:57.710
The opinions have
changed on this,

00:23:57.710 --> 00:24:00.560
but I like to use two parts
oil to one part acid when

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:01.990
you're making a vinaigrette.

00:24:01.990 --> 00:24:04.670
And then usually if you
don't want to be broken

00:24:04.670 --> 00:24:05.666
you can use a binder.

00:24:05.666 --> 00:24:06.165
JENNA: OK.

00:24:06.165 --> 00:24:08.670
AMANDA HAAS: So You can use as
much of a binder as you want.

00:24:08.670 --> 00:24:10.880
Some of the ones we
love to use, mustard,

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:14.000
so like a Dijon mustard, it'll
bring it all together for you,

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:18.170
mayonnaise I love mayonnaise
a little too much.

00:24:18.170 --> 00:24:20.750
You could use egg yolk, you
know that's a classic one.

00:24:20.750 --> 00:24:25.790
People also in very old styles
of cooking use blood, not a fan

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:26.544
personally.

00:24:26.544 --> 00:24:28.210
Haven't done that
since culinary school,

00:24:28.210 --> 00:24:30.812
and I probably will never again.

00:24:30.812 --> 00:24:31.520
JENNA: Maybe not.

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:33.228
AMANDA HAAS: Yeah,
no, I'll pass on that.

00:24:33.228 --> 00:24:34.110
Thank you very much.

00:24:34.110 --> 00:24:35.220
Not my thing.

00:24:35.220 --> 00:24:36.436
So I'm starting with garlic.

00:24:36.436 --> 00:24:38.310
And you could add any
aromatic that you want.

00:24:38.310 --> 00:24:40.350
You could add fresh
herbs if you want.

00:24:40.350 --> 00:24:42.544
You can add something
for sweetness.

00:24:42.544 --> 00:24:43.960
But now all I want
to do is I want

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:45.710
to start by adding my binder.

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:47.590
So Jenna, if you want
to put the Dijon in.

00:24:47.590 --> 00:24:48.780
Do you need a little spoon?

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:50.710
There you go.

00:24:50.710 --> 00:24:54.310
And then we have
a whisk for you.

00:24:54.310 --> 00:24:57.070
Perfect.

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:59.600
I start with a
pinch of salt, guys.

00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:01.810
And then now I want
you to take your acid.

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:03.949
So today we're
using lemon juice.

00:25:03.949 --> 00:25:06.490
This is kind of my version of
like a healthy Caesar dressing,

00:25:06.490 --> 00:25:07.810
if you wanted to do.

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:10.810
And I just want you
to whisk that in.

00:25:10.810 --> 00:25:12.680
If you wanted you
could use orange juice,

00:25:12.680 --> 00:25:14.545
lime juice, balsamic vinegar.

00:25:14.545 --> 00:25:15.670
You know there are so many.

00:25:15.670 --> 00:25:17.730
I use a lot of sherry vinegar.

00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:20.440
So completely depends
on your taste.

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:22.250
When I'm making
salads that I want

00:25:22.250 --> 00:25:25.930
to taste really fresh and clean,
I usually go toward citrus.

00:25:25.930 --> 00:25:28.632
I just love the flavor of strong
citrus in my vinaigrettes.

00:25:28.632 --> 00:25:29.340
JENNA: All right.

00:25:29.340 --> 00:25:30.670
AMANDA HAAS: So look
at how easy that is?

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:31.711
See, already figured out.

00:25:31.711 --> 00:25:33.440
So that was your one part acid.

00:25:33.440 --> 00:25:35.090
And now you need two parts oil.

00:25:35.090 --> 00:25:36.120
JENNA: All right, what
kind of oil are we using?

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:37.420
AMANDA HAAS: We're
going to use olive oil.

00:25:37.420 --> 00:25:39.211
And we're just going
to eyeball this again,

00:25:39.211 --> 00:25:40.952
crazy people that we are.

00:25:40.952 --> 00:25:42.160
JENNA: Getting crazy in here.

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:44.493
AMANDA HAAS: Yeah, so you can
add a little bit to start,

00:25:44.493 --> 00:25:45.620
and whisk it in.

00:25:45.620 --> 00:25:48.880
And you'll see it
start to come together.

00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:50.380
One of the coolest
things about this

00:25:50.380 --> 00:25:53.280
too is if you whisk too quickly,
and you're not emulsifying

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:54.860
as you go, doesn't matter.

00:25:54.860 --> 00:25:57.140
Just put it in a jar, and
shake it as hard as you can.

00:25:57.140 --> 00:26:00.080
And it'll bring
it back together.

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:01.810
You've clearly done
this once or twice.

00:26:01.810 --> 00:26:02.900
JENNA: I don't know
what you're talking.

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:04.360
AMANDA HAAS: Yeah, she's
like, no, I don't know.

00:26:04.360 --> 00:26:05.680
I just do it every day.

00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:07.020
JENNA: First time.

00:26:07.020 --> 00:26:08.920
AMANDA HAAS: But so
far, so good right?

00:26:08.920 --> 00:26:10.040
Not too hard to do.

00:26:10.040 --> 00:26:12.840
But it can totally change
the way your food tastes.

00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:16.560
And it's a really easy
thing to do at home.

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:18.820
My younger son thinks
he's super cool because he

00:26:18.820 --> 00:26:20.150
can make a vinaigrette right?

00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:21.240
And it sounds super fancy.

00:26:21.240 --> 00:26:22.110
JENNA: Pretty
cool, I don't know.

00:26:22.110 --> 00:26:23.310
AMANDA HAAS: Yeah.

00:26:23.310 --> 00:26:25.274
But it's nice to have around.

00:26:25.274 --> 00:26:26.690
Then when you come
home from work,

00:26:26.690 --> 00:26:28.360
it's so much easier
to make a salad.

00:26:28.360 --> 00:26:29.734
JENNA: You, make
the vinaigrette.

00:26:29.734 --> 00:26:30.620
You wash the greens.

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:30.870
AMANDA HAAS: Yes.

00:26:30.870 --> 00:26:31.630
JENNA: You, chop the veggies.

00:26:31.630 --> 00:26:32.130
AMANDA HAAS: Exactly.

00:26:32.130 --> 00:26:32.950
JENNA: I like it.

00:26:32.950 --> 00:26:33.930
AMANDA HAAS: Exactly.

00:26:33.930 --> 00:26:37.050
You'll just see all kinds of
Mason jars in my refrigerator.

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:39.300
It looks like a little
scientist's workshop, right.

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:43.200
There's balsamic, there's
a citrus one usually.

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:45.890
I like to do one if I'm
making Mexican food where--

00:26:45.890 --> 00:26:46.780
Oh, thank you.

00:26:46.780 --> 00:26:50.030
I've got my queue
to check my lentils.

00:26:50.030 --> 00:26:52.460
--I'll do some with like
a chipotle and adobo,

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:54.340
and use that as the base.

00:26:54.340 --> 00:26:56.710
And then add honey and
orange juice and oil.

00:26:56.710 --> 00:26:59.810
One of my favorites, or lime
juice should be good too.

00:26:59.810 --> 00:27:01.000
Check it out.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:02.090
This looks good.

00:27:02.090 --> 00:27:05.990
I'm going to taste, like
I promised you I would.

00:27:05.990 --> 00:27:06.630
Let's see.

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:13.112
It's tasty, but it needs
more salt, for sure.

00:27:16.290 --> 00:27:17.510
Oh let's add the veggies now.

00:27:17.510 --> 00:27:19.200
Let's be wild.

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:20.944
Not too much is
going to go wrong.

00:27:20.944 --> 00:27:23.360
That's the other thing about
cooking when people are like,

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:24.540
what if I mess it up?

00:27:24.540 --> 00:27:25.510
Guess what, who cares?

00:27:25.510 --> 00:27:26.830
It's so cool to be cooking.

00:27:26.830 --> 00:27:29.010
And people love when you
cook for them, right.

00:27:29.010 --> 00:27:30.930
And so sometimes we mess up.

00:27:30.930 --> 00:27:33.560
My family has to eat
all of my mistakes.

00:27:33.560 --> 00:27:35.130
There are a lot of them.

00:27:35.130 --> 00:27:37.400
JENNA: That's good
lessons always too.

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:39.380
Then what you did wrong,
you don't do it again.

00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:40.912
AMANDA HAAS: Absolutely.

00:27:40.912 --> 00:27:43.120
You know especially cooking
my way through this book,

00:27:43.120 --> 00:27:45.490
where I had to use
different ingredients than I

00:27:45.490 --> 00:27:48.300
was used to or more of
things than I was used to,

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:49.870
I messed up a ton.

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:51.540
But it's kind of fun.

00:27:51.540 --> 00:27:52.590
It's part of the journey.

